At the start of Week 16, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:43 p.m., already well into the evening of democratic risk. By the end of the period, it had moved forward to 7:45 p.m., a shift of 1.9 minutes. That change may seem small, but it reflected a broad deepening of traits that make reversal harder: a more politicized civil service, a media sphere tilted toward state-aligned outlets, a migration regime that treats due process as optional, and an economic order in which policy follows money. The clock moved because these were not isolated abuses; they were coordinated moves that changed structures, not just headlines. Even where courts or Congress pushed back, the net effect was to normalize a new baseline in which executive power operates with fewer effective checks.\
