The most visible front in this week\'92s struggle over power was the civil service itself. The story began months earlier with the DOGE-led \'93Valentine\'92s Day massacre,\'94 when thousands of probationary federal workers were fired across agencies. In Week 16, the consequences of that purge became clearer. Trump\'92s earlier order easing the firing of probationary employees remained in place, and the Office of Special Counsel, once a watchdog for civil servants, announced it was dropping its inquiry into whether those mass dismissals were unlawful. The Supreme Court\'92s intervention in the chaotic reinstatement process left many workers rehired only to be placed on leave and dismissed again. Job security in the federal government now depended less on neutral performance and more on political favor. The civil service, designed as a buffer between partisan will and public administration, was being remade as an instrument of that will.\
\
The hollowing out was not confined to anonymous staff. At the Environmental Protection Agency, the administration announced cuts that would take staffing back to 1980s levels and dissolve the Office of Research and Development, forcing 1,500 scientists to compete for 400 slots. At the National Institutes of Health, RFK Jr. fired another 200 employees, including 50 from the National Cancer Institute, on top of an earlier wave of dismissals. USAID lost more than 5,600 workers as DOGE-driven cuts caused life-saving medicines to expire in warehouses and halted HIV prevention programs abroad. FEMA\'92s director was fired after he publicly opposed eliminating the agency, just weeks before hurricane season. Each of these actions weakened the state\'92s capacity to protect health, environment, and safety, and each replaced expertise with a more pliable, thinner layer of loyal managers. The trait \'93civil service roles are politicized or privatized\'94 moved upward because these were not temporary budget trims; they were structural changes that would take years to undo.\
