Appointments at the top reinforced this pattern. Trump named Alina Habba, a personal lawyer with a partisan profile, as interim U.S. Attorney for New Jersey, and then installed Marco Rubio as acting national security adviser while he remained Secretary of State and took on other acting roles. Andrew Giuliani was tapped to lead the World Cup task force, and Dr Casey Means, a wellness influencer with unconventional views and little public health experience, was nominated as Surgeon General. Sid Rosenberg, a radio host with a record of racist remarks, was appointed to the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council. When Ed Martin\'92s nomination as D.C. U.S. Attorney stalled, Trump withdrew it and then placed him in charge of reviewing pardon requests at the Justice Department. These choices showed that loyalty and media value, not subject-matter competence, were the main currencies for high office. The trait \'93appointments awarded by loyalty and wealth\'94 deepened because the pattern now spanned law enforcement, national security, culture, and health. It was no longer an exception.\
