Alongside the reshaping of personnel came a quieter but equally important shift: the outsourcing of state power to private and often opaque actors. Elon Musk\'92s Department of Government Efficiency, or DOGE, sat at the center of this trend. DOGE had orchestrated the mass firing of civil servants and promised trillions in savings, only to deliver a fraction of that while leaving agencies in disarray. At the same time, it consolidated personal data on millions of citizens in ways that prompted at least eleven lawsuits alleging violations of the Privacy Act. The consolidation of records across immigration, Social Security, and other systems created a powerful tool for surveillance and targeting, but one largely shielded from traditional oversight. The trait \'93state power is outsourced to unaccountable private contractors\'94 rose because DOGE functioned less like a neutral efficiency office and more like a private political instrument embedded inside the state.\
