Trade and economic policy followed the same logic. The administration imposed a 10% global tariff and steep sector-specific duties on steel, autos, and other goods, branding April 2 \'93Liberation Day.\'94 It added a 25% tariff on imported auto parts, raising costs for manufacturers and consumers, and floated a 100% tariff on foreign films by labeling them a national security threat. When markets reacted and allies protested, the White House walked back some of the rhetoric, and later in the week Trump unilaterally cut a punitive tariff on China from 145% to 80% ahead of talks in Geneva, without extracting concessions. Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent dodged congressional questions about who pays tariffs, and official GDP releases framed import surges in misleading ways. The result was a sense of economic whiplash: tariffs announced, defended, and then revised in rapid succession, with little transparency about their real costs. The trait \'93policy outcomes are driven by elite lobbying and financial contributions\'94 rose because tariff carve-outs for big-oil donors and the influence of Trump-linked investors on trade decisions showed that those closest to power could shape the rules to their advantage.\
