If the administrative state and the economy were being re-engineered, the information sphere was being reshaped just as aggressively. In mid-March, Trump had signed an order dismantling the U.S. Agency for Global Media and effectively shutting down Voice of America, taking its broadcasts off the air for the first time since World War II and placing 1,300 employees on leave. In Week 16, that order remained in effect, with a divided appeals court staying a lower court\'92s attempt to restore the staff. At the same time, VoA\'92s parent company, under the influence of Kari Lake, contracted One America News, a hard-right outlet, to provide newsfeed and video services. The administration also issued an executive order cutting NPR and PBS off from federal funds through the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, a move that threatened the survival of small rural stations. These actions did not simply punish critical outlets; they redirected public resources toward state-aligned voices and partisan content. The trait \'93independent media is starved while state-aligned outlets thrive\'94 rose because the state was now both defunding neutral platforms and importing friendly ones into its own infrastructure.\
