Immigration and enforcement policy moved further toward a quasi-permanent emergency footing. The administration pursued a budget reconciliation bill that would increase ICE funding to historic levels: $45 billion for detention centers and $14.4 billion for transportation and removal over five years, enough to hire 10,000 new officers and make ICE the best-funded law enforcement agency in the country. At the same time, ICE was deputizing thousands of agents from the DEA, FBI, IRS, and other agencies to assist in immigration arrests, and headquarters in Washington required approval for any release from detention. Facilities became overcrowded, holding more people than Congress had funded. A new initiative offered $1,000 and free airfare to undocumented immigrants who chose to self-deport, but downplayed the ten-year reentry ban that would bar many from returning. Deportation flights to El Salvador carried people who had been legally residing in the U.S. and complying with rules, justified by claims about Venezuelan gangs that U.S. intelligence later disputed. The trait \'93citizenship is stratified by wealth, ideology, and heritage\'94 rose because the legal protections available to non-citizens were being narrowed by design, and because senior officials, including Trump and DHS Secretary Kristi Noem, publicly refused to affirm that everyone in the country is entitled to due process.\
